               <msContents>
                  <summary><title type="uniform">Óðalsbrigði</title></summary>
                  <msItem n="1" class="logfr" defective="false">
                     <locus from="1r" to="4r">1r-4r</locus>
                     <title type="uniform">Óðalsbrigði</title>
                     <textLang mainLang="is">Icelandic</textLang>
                     <rubric>Odal Balkur eda Landab<ex>ri</ex>gdab<ex>alkur</ex> ur Gulaþ<ex>ings</ex> bok: Cap. 1</rubric>
                     <incipit>Nu skipta m<ex>enn</ex> b<ex>rædur</ex> tveir e<ex>dur</ex> fleire ödul<ex>um</ex> syn ä mille</incipit>
                     <explicit>allt þat er i kaup þeirra kom:</explicit>
                     <note>Chap. 1-17 of King Magnus Hákonarson lagabætir's landslov</note>
                     <filiation>This is a copy of <ref type="ms" target="AM04-0059-a">AM 59 a 4to</ref> 
                        (<bibl>Storm:
                           <ref target="NgL4">Norges gamle Love</ref><biblScope unit="volume">IV</biblScope><biblScope unit="pages">546</biblScope></bibl>).</filiation>
                  
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               
               
               
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <support>Paper with watermark.
                           <watermark>There is a coat of arms of Amsterdam watermark on the <locus>front flyleaf</locus> and fol. <locus>4</locus>. 
                              Another watermark depicting a pair of wings or antlers (?) is visible on fol. <locus from="1r" to="1v">1</locus>.</watermark>
                        </support>
                        <extent>i + 4. <dimensions type="leaf" scope="all">
                           <height unit="mm" atLeast="200" atMost="203">200-203</height>
                           <width unit="mm" atLeast="162" atMost="164">162-164</width>
                        </dimensions>
                          
                        </extent>
                        
                        <foliation>
                           <p>There is possibly contemporary pagination in brown ink in the upper outer corner of every leaf, which is continued on the replacement leaf in the back (1-7). 
                              The flyleaf is not counted.</p>
                           <p>There is later foliation in pencil on the bottom of the recto pages (1-4). Again, the flyleaf is not counted.</p>
                        </foliation> 
                        <collation><p><list>
                           <item>I: Front flyleaf- fol. 4 (i + 4, 1, 2, 3), i.e. the flyleaf and the last leaf form a bifolium, the original leaves are three singletons.</item>
                        </list>
                        </p>
                           <catchwords>There are no catchwords.</catchwords>
                        </collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>The paper is in fairly good condition.</p>
                           <p>Some leaves have suffered damage at the edges.</p>
                           <p>The edges are untrimmed.</p>
                           <p>Remnants of earlier reapir is visible on the inner edge of 
                              fol. <locus>1</locus>, but has been replaced by Japanese tissue.</p>
                           <p>The singletons 2 + 3 have been joined using Japanese tissue. </p>
                           <p>The leaves are slightly discoloured from dirt, in particular around the edges.</p>
                           
                        </condition> 
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="1" writtenLines="28 30"> 
                           <p>The manuscript is written in one column with 28 to 30 lines per page and 18 to 20 words per line.</p>
                           <p>The dimensions of the written area are ca. <dimensions type="written"><height unit="mm" quantity="165">165</height>
                              <width unit="mm" atLeast="130" atMost="140">130-140</width></dimensions>.</p>
                           
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc hands="2">
                     <handNote scribe="unknown" scope="major" script="kanzlei"> 
                        <p>An unknown scribe wrote fols. <locus from="1r" to="3v">1r-3v</locus>.</p></handNote>
                     <handNote scribe="unknown" scope="minor" script="kanzlei">
                        <p>One of <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name>'s scribes wrote fol.
                           <locus from="4r" to="4r">4r</locus> (see <bibl>Kålund, <ref type="secondary-1" target="KKKat">Katalog</ref>
                              <biblScope unit="volume">I</biblScope><biblScope unit="pages">378</biblScope></bibl>).</p></handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="initial">The initials are hardly emphasized, but at times written somewhat larger (1-2 lines).</decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>  
                  <additions>
                     <p>
                        The front flyleaf and fol. <locus from="4r" to="4v">4</locus> form a bifolio which is a later addition from <name type="person">Árni Magnússon</name>'s time.
                     One of his scribes has written 
                        the end of the text on fol. <locus>4r</locus>.</p>
                     <p>The title <title type="uniform">Odals balkur.</title> is written in brown ink on the recto-side of the <locus>front flyleaf</locus> in 
                        <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name>'s hand.</p>
                     <p>On fol. <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v</locus> there is a later marginal note in the shape of a cross executed in pencil. 
                        On the same line, two words are underlined (also using pencil)</p>
                     <p>Fol. <locus>2r</locus> shows a marginal note in a different script type (kurrent instead of chancery), but is
                        presumably written by the main scribe.</p>
                     
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc><binding contemporary="false" notBefore="1771" notAfter="1780">
                     <p>The binding is made out of  cardboard covered in grey handmade paper. Printed material is used in the pastedowns.</p>
                     <p>The original shelfmark designation on the front cover is <q>AM 59 A</q> using black ink, corrected to <q>AM 59 B</q> by a later hand isung lighter ink. 
                        Below, the title <q>Odals bälkr.</q> is written in black ink.
                        The shelfmark is repeated several times in different hands inside the front cover and on the front flyleaf.</p>
                     <p>Stored in one box with <ref type="ms" target="AM04-0059-a">AM 59 a 4to</ref>.</p>
                  </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <accMat>
                     
                  </accMat>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin notBefore="1690" notAfter="1710" cert="medium" evidence="external">
                     <p>The manuscript was probably written in <origPlace key="IS">Iceland</origPlace>.</p>
                     <p><bibl>Kålund (<ref type="secondary-1" target="KKKat">Katalog</ref><biblScope unit="volume">I</biblScope><biblScope unit="pages">378</biblScope></bibl>) dates it to <origDate notBefore="1690" notAfter="1710">c. 1700</origDate>.</p>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>It is unclear if the added bifolium and note by <name type="person" key="ArnMag001">Árni Magnússon</name> with provenance information,
                        now found in <ref target="AM04-0059-a">AM 59 a 4to</ref>,
                        belongs to that copy or rather this. (See
                        also <bibl>Storm: <ref type="secondary-1" target="NgL4">Norges gamle
                           Love</ref><biblScope unit="volume">IV</biblScope> <biblScope unit="pages">546</biblScope>
                        </bibl>). </p>
                  </provenance>
               </history>
